Point is the fact that such a post is as immutable and uncensorable as it gets. Consider someone hosting an Tor website with a great deal of leaked information. Using Locked Posts, one can ensure such a link is never taken out of the public eye. Combined with ZeroNet, it has a secure channel to transmit the link, therefore that leak repository will stay up for as long as the server does.

Frankly, Locked Post should rotate signing keys in addition to any other security measure. By signing ZeroNet zites with rotating signing keys, making new zites as they go, they effectively put a time limit on brute forcing the private key, which is already almost impossible, making such an event highly improbably.

Let me explain
your PATH is an environment variable. Its value consists of a list of paths to folders on your computer, seperated by colons (usually, will be on Windows.)
When the OS needs to find an executable, it will search the list of folders contained within your PATH, looking for a program that matches the filename you are looking for
It will use the first one found, so if an updated version of the program is in a folder that comes after the first one, it will not be used.

Torrents CAN and usually do download faster, but the problem is that the file must be hosted by other peers, or a seedbox acting as a peer
It's the differences between HTTP(S) and BitTorrent that make it happen: with HTTP, you have your computer connected with a server, and if any one point in the chain fails, the entire download stalls

BitTorrent, on the other hand, splits a file up into uniformily (though variable) sized chunks, and sends only that chunk at a time. In addition, it makes multiple connections to multiple peers to download different parts of the file at the same time, maximizing your download bandwidth used.

Meaning, your client downloads the file from multiple peers at once, instead of relying entirely on the single server that HTTP does. When you have a piece of the given file, you act as a server to everyone else who wants a file, sending the chunks you have to everyone else so they can download the file too :)
While there is a technical difference between a server<>client scenario and a single seed <> single peer model, you probably wouldn't notice any difference besides the program you use to download

When the file is popular wanted/seeded by multiple people, however, BitTorrent can be much, MUCH faster than any HTTP stream could hope to be. The fact that it is used by pirates a great deal is actually a gigantic stumbling block in the BitTorrent company's way to widespread adoption, due to the stigma associated with it
